    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_531093">Well, after seeing my Ready Player One thread pop to the top a few times, I decided that it was about time that I share a couple books I read (listened to... whatever) afterwards. Specifically Daemon and its sequel Freedom(TM) by Daniel Suarez. In (unintentionally) keeping with the theme of massively rich and eccentric super genius video game programmers dying at the beginning books, massively rich and eccentric super genius video game programmer Matthew Sobol dies at the beginning of Daemon, and sets off a chain of events that will change the world...<br />
<br />
More specifically, Daemon submits for your approval an alternate reality set in the USA that could very well be today -- Give or take a few years -- wherein Sobol has created a daemon (of the Unix variety, not biblical) to carry on his will after his death. It begins simply with the calculated murders of a few key programmers, and evolves into a massively distributed computer &quot;virus&quot; spanning the globe with no obvious way to stop it. The sequel, Freedom(TM) continues just a few months after the end of Daemon, in a world now fully in the grips of an insane programmer's magnum opus, one faction of humanity trying to help it, the other trying to destroy (or control) it.<br />
<br />
Suffice to say, by the end of the second book, I was starting to wish that it was non-fiction for a number of reasons. Daniel Suarez exhibits a deep mastery of all things tech, while also being capable of making it entertaining and understandable to someone who has only the slightest grasp of technology.  Through about the first 2/3 of Daemon, just about all the technology utilized is almost entirely plausible in today's world, with maybe a few more years to perfect it; with the last few chapters taking a dip more into the science fiction territory (though not in entirely implausible ways). Freedom(TM) has plenty of devices in it which can be firmly classified as science-fiction today, but most if not all of them are scientifically possible, if not entirely plausible with today's level of technology. Of course, Freedom(TM) also heavily features a society built around an MMO's structure, with levels, a currency, and unlockable abilities... which is reason enough for all of you to go out and pick these books up today!<br />
<br />
<br />
<i>EDIT -- 12/17/12 additional books below:</i><br />
<br />
All this talk of books in other threads has reminded me that I wanted to add a few more recommendations into this thread, as I have been chewing through them like MAD with my Audible subscription <img src="images/smilies/emote_laugh.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Laughing out loud" class="inlineimg" /><br />
And for that reason, I'm going to be adding recommendations and little reviews of the books below as I get time... for now, this will be a quick list of books I felt were good enough to recommend that you all go start reading them now :p<br />
<br />
<br />
The Lost Fleet - Jack Campbell (6 books main series, 9 total books with more on the way as of this writing)<br />
<br />
More or less, this series gives the absolute best (and most realistic) description of what real battles would be like in space, now with REAL PHYSICS! Captain John &quot;Black Jack&quot; Geary has been lost in space, frozen in an escape pod for over a century and is discovered by the Alliance Fleet on their way to what they think is going to be the final battle in a war which was started in the very same attack that resulted in Geary fleeing his dying ship. Through a series of events, he gains leadership of the whole fleet and must now get it safely home from the very center of enemy space. The author takes into account the laws of our universe as we understand them to present an amazing depiction of how war might actually be waged in space, taking into account things like the speed of light and the limitations it presents with communications and firing weapons systems. All in all, it is a fantastic story which had me unable to put the books down until I had finished them, in a few cases making it through an entire book in one sitting.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Snow Crash - Neal Stephenson<br />
<br />
What is there really to say about Snow Crash? I mean, it's a fantastic book... you can see direct ties between it and Second Life... One Google co-founder has flat out said that they were inspired by this book to create Google Earth... Err, right, there's supposed to be a review here!<br />
Snow Crash is one of those books that you know if you'll enjoy within the first few pages, though I will also say that if an American samurai/computer hacker delivering pizzas for the mafia seems ridiculous to you, at least finish the second chapter before putting the book down. The story takes place in a post economic collapse not-too-distant future version of the US, which is now a patchwork of corporate-franchise city-states, and the internet has become the Metaverse -- something much more akin to Second Life than what we're used to today. Here, Hiro Protagonist and Y.T. learn about a new drug, &quot;Snow Crash,&quot; which alters the mind in the real world, and can infect the brains of unwary hackers in the Metaverse. <br />
Personally, I loved this book, and it definitely belongs in the library of anybody who likes cyberpunk settings... though unlike a lot of cyberpunk media, Snow Crash has a fantastic sense of humor (A particular email about toilet paper usage in the workplace was quite fantastic...) Some might say that the book is a bit dated now in terms of the tech involved, though in 1992 it was pretty forward thinking... now a fair amount of what Stephenson described is a reality in one way or another, though I suppose it is a sign of a good sci-fi world when concepts and devices in it make it to the real world <img src="images/smilies/emote_wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Wink" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Reamde - Neal Stephenson<br />
<br />
Diamond Age - Neal Stephenson (Noticing a pattern here...)<br />
<br />
Pandora's Star &amp; Judas Unchained - Peter F. Hamilton</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
