    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_533410"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Pearll said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">To be fair, Star Trek and Star Wars are more &quot;marketable sci-fi&quot; than &quot;serious sci-fi&quot;.  They're designed to appeal to a larger range of audiences that don't really care about physics.  In the case of Star Trek, it's a soap opera set in space, focusing on the characters as much as (or more than) the situation, especially starting with TNG.<br />
<br />
This doesn't make these two series any less valid than other sci-fi, though, as both are entertaining.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Oh, I'm certainly not saying that Trek/Wars are any less good because of it... just that after The Lost Fleet, I see these (Star Wars especially) and can't help but think about the physics of it all now. I still enjoy them on their own merits, but it's still interesting to think about how different it would be if they were constrained to light speed communications and sensors... it's easy enough to just assume that the technology in those universes has advanced to the point where they do have sensors and communications systems which work faster than light. <br />
But The Lost Fleet paints a fantastic picture of what war would be like in space with the tech we have now... you know, with interstellar space craft with advanced weapons, shields, sensors, and communications systems, capable of reaching speeds upwards of 0.3 light speed, and a few things which really had to be thrown in just to make the whole story <i>work</i> (i.e.: Faster than light travel is a thing, but there are serious limitations on it) But you know... that's pretty standard for suspension of disbelief in sci-fi :p<br />
<br />
Really it mostly boils down to the fact that The Lost Fleet is more hard sci-fi, and Star Wars... well... much less so :p Star Trek is certainly still somewhat hard sci-fi for a number of reasons, though as an article I read recently put it, &quot;the technology is usually powered by handwavium.&quot;</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
